8 """The schema module provides the building blocks for database metadata.
9  
10 Each element within this module describes a database entity which can be
11 created and dropped, or is otherwise part of such an entity. Examples include
12 tables, columns, sequences, and indexes.
13  
14 All entities are subclasses of :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.SchemaItem`, and as
15 defined in this module they are intended to be agnostic of any vendor-specific
16 constructs.
17  
18 A collection of entities are grouped into a unit called
19 :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.MetaData`. MetaData serves as a logical grouping of
20 schema elements, and can also be associated with an actual database connection
21 such that operations involving the contained elements can contact the database
22 as needed.
23  
24 Two of the elements here also build upon their "syntactic" counterparts, which
25 are defined in :class:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.`, specifically
26 :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.Table` and :class:`~sqlalchemy.schema.Column`.
27 Since these objects are part of the SQL expression language, they are usable
28 as components in SQL expressions.
29  
30 """

169 class Table(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem, TableClause):
170 r"""Represent a table in a database.
171  
172 e.g.::
173  
174 mytable = Table("mytable", metadata,
175 Column('mytable_id', Integer, primary_key=True),
176 Column('value', String(50))
177 )
178  
179 The :class:`_schema.Table`
180 object constructs a unique instance of itself based
181 on its name and optional schema name within the given
182 :class:`_schema.MetaData` object. Calling the :class:`_schema.Table`
183 constructor with the same name and same :class:`_schema.MetaData` argument
184 a second time will return the *same* :class:`_schema.Table`
185 object - in this way
186 the :class:`_schema.Table` constructor acts as a registry function.
187  
188 .. seealso::
189  
190 :ref:`metadata_describing` - Introduction to database metadata
191  
192 Constructor arguments are as follows:
193  
194 :param name: The name of this table as represented in the database.
195  
196 The table name, along with the value of the ``schema`` parameter,
197 forms a key which uniquely identifies this :class:`_schema.Table`
198 within
199 the owning :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection.
200 Additional calls to :class:`_schema.Table` with the same name,
201 metadata,
202 and schema name will return the same :class:`_schema.Table` object.
203  
204 Names which contain no upper case characters
205 will be treated as case insensitive names, and will not be quoted
206 unless they are a reserved word or contain special characters.
207 A name with any number of upper case characters is considered
208 to be case sensitive, and will be sent as quoted.
209  
210 To enable unconditional quoting for the table name, specify the flag
211 ``quote=True`` to the constructor, or use the :class:`.quoted_name`
212 construct to specify the name.
213  
214 :param metadata: a :class:`_schema.MetaData`
215 object which will contain this
216 table. The metadata is used as a point of association of this table
217 with other tables which are referenced via foreign key. It also
218 may be used to associate this table with a particular
219 :class:`.Connectable`.
220  
221 :param \*args: Additional positional arguments are used primarily
222 to add the list of :class:`_schema.Column`
223 objects contained within this
224 table. Similar to the style of a CREATE TABLE statement, other
225 :class:`.SchemaItem` constructs may be added here, including
226 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint`, and
227 :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint`.
228  
229 :param autoload: Defaults to False, unless
230 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload_with`
231 is set in which case it defaults to True; :class:`_schema.Column`
232 objects
233 for this table should be reflected from the database, possibly
234 augmenting or replacing existing :class:`_schema.Column`
235 objects that were
236 explicitly specified.
237  
238 .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0 setting the
239 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload_with`
240 parameter implies that :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
241 will default
242 to True.
243  
244 .. seealso::
245  
246 :ref:`metadata_reflection_toplevel`
247  
248 :param autoload_replace: Defaults to ``True``; when using
249 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
250 in conjunction with :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`,
251 indicates
252 that :class:`_schema.Column` objects present in the already-existing
253 :class:`_schema.Table`
254 object should be replaced with columns of the same
255 name retrieved from the autoload process. When ``False``, columns
256 already present under existing names will be omitted from the
257 reflection process.
258  
259 Note that this setting does not impact :class:`_schema.Column` objects
260 specified programmatically within the call to :class:`_schema.Table`
261 that
262 also is autoloading; those :class:`_schema.Column` objects will always
263 replace existing columns of the same name when
264 :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing` is ``True``.
265  
266 .. seealso::
267  
268 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
269  
270 :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`
271  
272 :param autoload_with: An :class:`_engine.Engine` or
273 :class:`_engine.Connection` object
274 with which this :class:`_schema.Table` object will be reflected; when
275 set to a non-None value, it implies that
276 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
277 is ``True``. If left unset, but :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
278 is
279 explicitly set to ``True``, an autoload operation will attempt to
280 proceed by locating an :class:`_engine.Engine` or
281 :class:`_engine.Connection` bound
282 to the underlying :class:`_schema.MetaData` object.
283  
284 .. seealso::
285  
286 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
287  
288 :param extend_existing: When ``True``, indicates that if this
289 :class:`_schema.Table` is already present in the given
290 :class:`_schema.MetaData`,
291 apply further arguments within the constructor to the existing
292 :class:`_schema.Table`.
293  
294 If :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing` or
295 :paramref:`_schema.Table.keep_existing` are not set,
296 and the given name
297 of the new :class:`_schema.Table` refers to a :class:`_schema.Table`
298 that is
299 already present in the target :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection,
300 and
301 this :class:`_schema.Table`
302 specifies additional columns or other constructs
303 or flags that modify the table's state, an
304 error is raised. The purpose of these two mutually-exclusive flags
305 is to specify what action should be taken when a
306 :class:`_schema.Table`
307 is specified that matches an existing :class:`_schema.Table`,
308 yet specifies
309 additional constructs.
310  
311 :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`
312 will also work in conjunction
313 with :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload` to run a new reflection
314 operation against the database, even if a :class:`_schema.Table`
315 of the same name is already present in the target
316 :class:`_schema.MetaData`; newly reflected :class:`_schema.Column`
317 objects
318 and other options will be added into the state of the
319 :class:`_schema.Table`, potentially overwriting existing columns
320 and options of the same name.
321  
322 As is always the case with :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`,
323 :class:`_schema.Column` objects can be specified in the same
324 :class:`_schema.Table`
325 constructor, which will take precedence. Below, the existing
326 table ``mytable`` will be augmented with :class:`_schema.Column`
327 objects
328 both reflected from the database, as well as the given
329 :class:`_schema.Column`
330 named "y"::
331  
332 Table("mytable", metadata,
333 Column('y', Integer),
334 extend_existing=True,
335 autoload=True,
336 autoload_with=engine
337 )
338  
339 .. seealso::
340  
341 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload`
342  
343 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload_replace`
344  
345 :paramref:`_schema.Table.keep_existing`
346  
347  
348 :param implicit_returning: True by default - indicates that
349 RETURNING can be used by default to fetch newly inserted primary key
350 values, for backends which support this. Note that
351 :func:`_sa.create_engine` also provides an ``implicit_returning``
352 flag.
353  
354 :param include_columns: A list of strings indicating a subset of
355 columns to be loaded via the ``autoload`` operation; table columns who
356 aren't present in this list will not be represented on the resulting
357 ``Table`` object. Defaults to ``None`` which indicates all columns
358 should be reflected.
359  
360 :param resolve_fks: Whether or not to reflect :class:`_schema.Table`
361 objects
362 related to this one via :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` objects, when
363 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload` or
364 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload_with` is
365 specified. Defaults to True. Set to False to disable reflection of
366 related tables as :class:`_schema.ForeignKey`
367 objects are encountered; may be
368 used either to save on SQL calls or to avoid issues with related tables
369 that can't be accessed. Note that if a related table is already present
370 in the :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection, or becomes present later,
371 a
372 :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` object associated with this
373 :class:`_schema.Table` will
374 resolve to that table normally.
375  
376 .. versionadded:: 1.3
377  
378 .. seealso::
379  
380 :paramref:`.MetaData.reflect.resolve_fks`
381  
382  
383 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the
384 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object.
385  
386 :param keep_existing: When ``True``, indicates that if this Table
387 is already present in the given :class:`_schema.MetaData`, ignore
388 further arguments within the constructor to the existing
389 :class:`_schema.Table`, and return the :class:`_schema.Table`
390 object as
391 originally created. This is to allow a function that wishes
392 to define a new :class:`_schema.Table` on first call, but on
393 subsequent calls will return the same :class:`_schema.Table`,
394 without any of the declarations (particularly constraints)
395 being applied a second time.
396  
397 If :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing` or
398 :paramref:`_schema.Table.keep_existing` are not set,
399 and the given name
400 of the new :class:`_schema.Table` refers to a :class:`_schema.Table`
401 that is
402 already present in the target :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection,
403 and
404 this :class:`_schema.Table`
405 specifies additional columns or other constructs
406 or flags that modify the table's state, an
407 error is raised. The purpose of these two mutually-exclusive flags
408 is to specify what action should be taken when a
409 :class:`_schema.Table`
410 is specified that matches an existing :class:`_schema.Table`,
411 yet specifies
412 additional constructs.
413  
414 .. seealso::
415  
416 :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`
417  
418 :param listeners: A list of tuples of the form ``(<eventname>, <fn>)``
419 which will be passed to :func:`.event.listen` upon construction.
420 This alternate hook to :func:`.event.listen` allows the establishment
421 of a listener function specific to this :class:`_schema.Table` before
422 the "autoload" process begins. Particularly useful for
423 the :meth:`.DDLEvents.column_reflect` event::
424  
425 def listen_for_reflect(table, column_info):
426 "handle the column reflection event"
427 # ...
428  
429 t = Table(
430 'sometable',
431 autoload=True,
432 listeners=[
433 ('column_reflect', listen_for_reflect)
434 ])
435  
436 :param mustexist: When ``True``, indicates that this Table must already
437 be present in the given :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection, else
438 an exception is raised.
439  
440 :param prefixes:
441 A list of strings to insert after CREATE in the CREATE TABLE
442 statement. They will be separated by spaces.
443  
444 :param quote: Force quoting of this table's name on or off, corresponding
445 to ``True`` or ``False``. When left at its default of ``None``,
446 the column identifier will be quoted according to whether the name is
447 case sensitive (identifiers with at least one upper case character are
448 treated as case sensitive), or if it's a reserved word. This flag
449 is only needed to force quoting of a reserved word which is not known
450 by the SQLAlchemy dialect.
451  
452 :param quote_schema: same as 'quote' but applies to the schema identifier.
453  
454 :param schema: The schema name for this table, which is required if
455 the table resides in a schema other than the default selected schema
456 for the engine's database connection. Defaults to ``None``.
457  
458 If the owning :class:`_schema.MetaData` of this :class:`_schema.Table`
459 specifies its
460 own :paramref:`_schema.MetaData.schema` parameter,
461 then that schema name will
462 be applied to this :class:`_schema.Table`
463 if the schema parameter here is set
464 to ``None``. To set a blank schema name on a :class:`_schema.Table`
465 that
466 would otherwise use the schema set on the owning
467 :class:`_schema.MetaData`,
468 specify the special symbol :attr:`.BLANK_SCHEMA`.
469  
470 .. versionadded:: 1.0.14 Added the :attr:`.BLANK_SCHEMA` symbol to
471 allow a :class:`_schema.Table`
472 to have a blank schema name even when the
473 parent :class:`_schema.MetaData` specifies
474 :paramref:`_schema.MetaData.schema`.
475  
476 The quoting rules for the schema name are the same as those for the
477 ``name`` parameter, in that quoting is applied for reserved words or
478 case-sensitive names; to enable unconditional quoting for the schema
479 name, specify the flag ``quote_schema=True`` to the constructor, or use
480 the :class:`.quoted_name` construct to specify the name.
481  
482 :param useexisting: the same as :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`.
483  
484 :param comment: Optional string that will render an SQL comment on table
485 creation.
486  
487 .. versionadded:: 1.2 Added the :paramref:`_schema.Table.comment`
488 parameter
489 to :class:`_schema.Table`.
490  
491 :param \**kw: Additional keyword arguments not mentioned above are
492 dialect specific, and passed in the form ``<dialectname>_<argname>``.
493 See the documentation regarding an individual dialect at
494 :ref:`dialect_toplevel` for detail on documented arguments.
495  
496 """

731 include_columns = kwargs.pop("include_columns", None)
732  
733 resolve_fks = kwargs.pop("resolve_fks", True)
734  
735 if include_columns is not None:
736 for c in self.c:
737 if c.name not in include_columns:
738 self._columns.remove(c)
739  
740 for key in ("quote", "quote_schema"):
741 if key in kwargs:
742 raise exc.ArgumentError(
743 "Can't redefine 'quote' or 'quote_schema' arguments"
744 )
745  
746 if "comment" in kwargs:
747 self.comment = kwargs.pop("comment", None)
748  
749 if "info" in kwargs:
750 self.info = kwargs.pop("info")
751  
752 if autoload:
753 if not autoload_replace:
754 # don't replace columns already present.
755 # we'd like to do this for constraints also however we don't
756 # have simple de-duping for unnamed constraints.
757 exclude_columns = [c.name for c in self.c]
758 else:
759 exclude_columns = ()
760 self._autoload(
761 self.metadata,
762 autoload_with,
763 include_columns,
764 exclude_columns,
765 resolve_fks,
766 _extend_on=_extend_on,
767 )
768  
769 self._extra_kwargs(**kwargs)
770 self._init_items(*args)

944 def tometadata(
945 self,
946 metadata,
947 schema=RETAIN_SCHEMA,
948 referred_schema_fn=None,
949 name=None,
950 ):
951 """Return a copy of this :class:`_schema.Table`
952 associated with a different
953 :class:`_schema.MetaData`.
954  
955 E.g.::
956  
957 m1 = MetaData()
958  
959 user = Table('user', m1, Column('id', Integer, primary_key=True))
960  
961 m2 = MetaData()
962 user_copy = user.tometadata(m2)
963  
964 :param metadata: Target :class:`_schema.MetaData` object,
965 into which the
966 new :class:`_schema.Table` object will be created.
967  
968 :param schema: optional string name indicating the target schema.
969 Defaults to the special symbol :attr:`.RETAIN_SCHEMA` which indicates
970 that no change to the schema name should be made in the new
971 :class:`_schema.Table`. If set to a string name, the new
972 :class:`_schema.Table`
973 will have this new name as the ``.schema``. If set to ``None``, the
974 schema will be set to that of the schema set on the target
975 :class:`_schema.MetaData`, which is typically ``None`` as well,
976 unless
977 set explicitly::
978  
979 m2 = MetaData(schema='newschema')
980  
981 # user_copy_one will have "newschema" as the schema name
982 user_copy_one = user.tometadata(m2, schema=None)
983  
984 m3 = MetaData() # schema defaults to None
985  
986 # user_copy_two will have None as the schema name
987 user_copy_two = user.tometadata(m3, schema=None)
988  
989 :param referred_schema_fn: optional callable which can be supplied
990 in order to provide for the schema name that should be assigned
991 to the referenced table of a :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint`.
992 The callable accepts this parent :class:`_schema.Table`, the
993 target schema that we are changing to, the
994 :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint` object, and the existing
995 "target schema" of that constraint. The function should return the
996 string schema name that should be applied.
997 E.g.::
998  
999 def referred_schema_fn(table, to_schema,
1000 constraint, referred_schema):
1001 if referred_schema == 'base_tables':
1002 return referred_schema
1003 else:
1004 return to_schema
1005  
1006 new_table = table.tometadata(m2, schema="alt_schema",
1007 referred_schema_fn=referred_schema_fn)
1008  
1009 .. versionadded:: 0.9.2
1010  
1011 :param name: optional string name indicating the target table name.
1012 If not specified or None, the table name is retained. This allows
1013 a :class:`_schema.Table` to be copied to the same
1014 :class:`_schema.MetaData` target
1015 with a new name.
1016  
1017 .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
1018  
1019 """
1020 if name is None:
1021 name = self.name
1022 if schema is RETAIN_SCHEMA:
1023 schema = self.schema
1024 elif schema is None:
1025 schema = metadata.schema
1026 key = _get_table_key(name, schema)
1027 if key in metadata.tables:
1028 util.warn(
1029 "Table '%s' already exists within the given "
1030 "MetaData - not copying." % self.description
1031 )
1032 return metadata.tables[key]
1033  
1034 args = []
1035 for c in self.columns:
1036 args.append(c.copy(schema=schema))
1037 table = Table(
1038 name,
1039 metadata,
1040 schema=schema,
1041 comment=self.comment,
1042 *args,
1043 **self.kwargs
1044 )
1045 for c in self.constraints:
1046 if isinstance(c, ForeignKeyConstraint):
1047 referred_schema = c._referred_schema
1048 if referred_schema_fn:
1049 fk_constraint_schema = referred_schema_fn(
1050 self, schema, c, referred_schema
1051 )
1052 else:
1053 fk_constraint_schema = (
1054 schema if referred_schema == self.schema else None
1055 )
1056 table.append_constraint(
1057 c.copy(schema=fk_constraint_schema, target_table=table)
1058 )
1059 elif not c._type_bound:
1060 # skip unique constraints that would be generated
1061 # by the 'unique' flag on Column
1062 if c._column_flag:
1063 continue
1064  
1065 table.append_constraint(
1066 c.copy(schema=schema, target_table=table)
1067 )
1068 for index in self.indexes:
1069 # skip indexes that would be generated
1070 # by the 'index' flag on Column
1071 if index._column_flag:
1072 continue
1073 Index(
1074 index.name,
1075 unique=index.unique,
1076 *[
1077 _copy_expression(expr, self, table)
1078 for expr in index.expressions
1079 ],
1080 _table=table,
1081 **index.kwargs
1082 )
1083 return self._schema_item_copy(table)

1086 class Column(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem, ColumnClause):
1087 """Represents a column in a database table."""
1088  
1089 __visit_name__ = "column"
1090  
1091 def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
1092 r"""
1093 Construct a new ``Column`` object.
1094  
1095 :param name: The name of this column as represented in the database.
1096 This argument may be the first positional argument, or specified
1097 via keyword.
1098  
1099 Names which contain no upper case characters
1100 will be treated as case insensitive names, and will not be quoted
1101 unless they are a reserved word. Names with any number of upper
1102 case characters will be quoted and sent exactly. Note that this
1103 behavior applies even for databases which standardize upper
1104 case names as case insensitive such as Oracle.
1105  
1106 The name field may be omitted at construction time and applied
1107 later, at any time before the Column is associated with a
1108 :class:`_schema.Table`. This is to support convenient
1109 usage within the :mod:`~sqlalchemy.ext.declarative` extension.
1110  
1111 :param type\_: The column's type, indicated using an instance which
1112 subclasses :class:`~sqlalchemy.types.TypeEngine`. If no arguments
1113 are required for the type, the class of the type can be sent
1114 as well, e.g.::
1115  
1116 # use a type with arguments
1117 Column('data', String(50))
1118  
1119 # use no arguments
1120 Column('level', Integer)
1121  
1122 The ``type`` argument may be the second positional argument
1123 or specified by keyword.
1124  
1125 If the ``type`` is ``None`` or is omitted, it will first default to
1126 the special type :class:`.NullType`. If and when this
1127 :class:`_schema.Column` is made to refer to another column using
1128 :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` and/or
1129 :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint`, the type
1130 of the remote-referenced column will be copied to this column as
1131 well, at the moment that the foreign key is resolved against that
1132 remote :class:`_schema.Column` object.
1133  
1134 .. versionchanged:: 0.9.0
1135 Support for propagation of type to a :class:`_schema.Column`
1136 from its
1137 :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` object has been improved and should be
1138 more reliable and timely.
1139  
1140 :param \*args: Additional positional arguments include various
1141 :class:`.SchemaItem` derived constructs which will be applied
1142 as options to the column. These include instances of
1143 :class:`.Constraint`, :class:`_schema.ForeignKey`,
1144 :class:`.ColumnDefault`,
1145 :class:`.Sequence`, :class:`.Computed`. In some cases an
1146 equivalent keyword argument is available such as ``server_default``,
1147 ``default`` and ``unique``.
1148  
1149 :param autoincrement: Set up "auto increment" semantics for an integer
1150 primary key column. The default value is the string ``"auto"``
1151 which indicates that a single-column primary key that is of
1152 an INTEGER type with no stated client-side or python-side defaults
1153 should receive auto increment semantics automatically;
1154 all other varieties of primary key columns will not. This
1155 includes that :term:`DDL` such as PostgreSQL SERIAL or MySQL
1156 AUTO_INCREMENT will be emitted for this column during a table
1157 create, as well as that the column is assumed to generate new
1158 integer primary key values when an INSERT statement invokes which
1159 will be retrieved by the dialect.
1160  
1161 The flag may be set to ``True`` to indicate that a column which
1162 is part of a composite (e.g. multi-column) primary key should
1163 have autoincrement semantics, though note that only one column
1164 within a primary key may have this setting. It can also
1165 be set to ``True`` to indicate autoincrement semantics on a
1166 column that has a client-side or server-side default configured,
1167 however note that not all dialects can accommodate all styles
1168 of default as an "autoincrement". It can also be
1169 set to ``False`` on a single-column primary key that has a
1170 datatype of INTEGER in order to disable auto increment semantics
1171 for that column.
1172  
1173 .. versionchanged:: 1.1 The autoincrement flag now defaults to
1174 ``"auto"`` which indicates autoincrement semantics by default
1175 for single-column integer primary keys only; for composite
1176 (multi-column) primary keys, autoincrement is never implicitly
1177 enabled; as always, ``autoincrement=True`` will allow for
1178 at most one of those columns to be an "autoincrement" column.
1179 ``autoincrement=True`` may also be set on a
1180 :class:`_schema.Column`
1181 that has an explicit client-side or server-side default,
1182 subject to limitations of the backend database and dialect.
1183  
1184  
1185 The setting *only* has an effect for columns which are:
1186  
1187 * Integer derived (i.e. INT, SMALLINT, BIGINT).
1188  
1189 * Part of the primary key
1190  
1191 * Not referring to another column via :class:`_schema.ForeignKey`,
1192 unless
1193 the value is specified as ``'ignore_fk'``::
1194  
1195 # turn on autoincrement for this column despite
1196 # the ForeignKey()
1197 Column('id', ForeignKey('other.id'),
1198 primary_key=True, autoincrement='ignore_fk')
1199  
1200 It is typically not desirable to have "autoincrement" enabled on a
1201 column that refers to another via foreign key, as such a column is
1202 required to refer to a value that originates from elsewhere.
1203  
1204 The setting has these two effects on columns that meet the
1205 above criteria:
1206  
1207 * DDL issued for the column will include database-specific
1208 keywords intended to signify this column as an
1209 "autoincrement" column, such as AUTO INCREMENT on MySQL,
1210 SERIAL on PostgreSQL, and IDENTITY on MS-SQL. It does
1211 *not* issue AUTOINCREMENT for SQLite since this is a
1212 special SQLite flag that is not required for autoincrementing
1213 behavior.
1214  
1215 .. seealso::
1216  
1217 :ref:`sqlite_autoincrement`
1218  
1219 * The column will be considered to be available using an
1220 "autoincrement" method specific to the backend database, such
1221 as calling upon ``cursor.lastrowid``, using RETURNING in an
1222 INSERT statement to get at a sequence-generated value, or using
1223 special functions such as "SELECT scope_identity()".
1224 These methods are highly specific to the DBAPIs and databases in
1225 use and vary greatly, so care should be taken when associating
1226 ``autoincrement=True`` with a custom default generation function.
1227  
1228  
1229 :param default: A scalar, Python callable, or
1230 :class:`_expression.ColumnElement` expression representing the
1231 *default value* for this column, which will be invoked upon insert
1232 if this column is otherwise not specified in the VALUES clause of
1233 the insert. This is a shortcut to using :class:`.ColumnDefault` as
1234 a positional argument; see that class for full detail on the
1235 structure of the argument.
1236  
1237 Contrast this argument to
1238 :paramref:`_schema.Column.server_default`
1239 which creates a default generator on the database side.
1240  
1241 .. seealso::
1242  
1243 :ref:`metadata_defaults_toplevel`
1244  
1245 :param doc: optional String that can be used by the ORM or similar
1246 to document attributes on the Python side. This attribute does
1247 **not** render SQL comments; use the
1248 :paramref:`_schema.Column.comment`
1249 parameter for this purpose.
1250  
1251 :param key: An optional string identifier which will identify this
1252 ``Column`` object on the :class:`_schema.Table`.
1253 When a key is provided,
1254 this is the only identifier referencing the ``Column`` within the
1255 application, including ORM attribute mapping; the ``name`` field
1256 is used only when rendering SQL.
1257  
1258 :param index: When ``True``, indicates that a :class:`_schema.Index`
1259 construct will be automatically generated for this
1260 :class:`_schema.Column`, which will result in a "CREATE INDEX"
1261 statement being emitted for the :class:`_schema.Table` when the DDL
1262 create operation is invoked.
1263  
1264 Using this flag is equivalent to making use of the
1265 :class:`_schema.Index` construct explicitly at the level of the
1266 :class:`_schema.Table` construct itself::
1267  
1268 Table(
1269 "some_table",
1270 metadata,
1271 Column("x", Integer),
1272 Index("ix_some_table_x", "x")
1273 )
1274  
1275 To add the :paramref:`_schema.Index.unique` flag to the
1276 :class:`_schema.Index`, set both the
1277 :paramref:`_schema.Column.unique` and
1278 :paramref:`_schema.Column.index` flags to True simultaneously,
1279 which will have the effect of rendering the "CREATE UNIQUE INDEX"
1280 DDL instruction instead of "CREATE INDEX".
1281  
1282 The name of the index is generated using the
1283 :ref:`default naming convention <constraint_default_naming_convention>`
1284 which for the :class:`_schema.Index` construct is of the form
1285 ``ix_<tablename>_<columnname>``.
1286  
1287 As this flag is intended only as a convenience for the common case
1288 of adding a single-column, default configured index to a table
1289 definition, explicit use of the :class:`_schema.Index` construct
1290 should be preferred for most use cases, including composite indexes
1291 that encompass more than one column, indexes with SQL expressions
1292 or ordering, backend-specific index configuration options, and
1293 indexes that use a specific name.
1294  
1295 .. note:: the :attr:`_schema.Column.index` attribute on
1296 :class:`_schema.Column`
1297 **does not indicate** if this column is indexed or not, only
1298 if this flag was explicitly set here. To view indexes on
1299 a column, view the :attr:`_schema.Table.indexes` collection
1300 or use :meth:`_reflection.Inspector.get_indexes`.
1301  
1302 .. seealso::
1303  
1304 :ref:`schema_indexes`
1305  
1306 :ref:`constraint_naming_conventions`
1307  
1308 :paramref:`_schema.Column.unique`
1309  
1310 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the
1311 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object.
1312  
1313 :param nullable: When set to ``False``, will cause the "NOT NULL"
1314 phrase to be added when generating DDL for the column. When
1315 ``True``, will normally generate nothing (in SQL this defaults to
1316 "NULL"), except in some very specific backend-specific edge cases
1317 where "NULL" may render explicitly. Defaults to ``True`` unless
1318 :paramref:`_schema.Column.primary_key` is also ``True``,
1319 in which case it
1320 defaults to ``False``. This parameter is only used when issuing
1321 CREATE TABLE statements.
1322  
1323 :param onupdate: A scalar, Python callable, or
1324 :class:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.ClauseElement` representing a
1325 default value to be applied to the column within UPDATE
1326 statements, which will be invoked upon update if this column is not
1327 present in the SET clause of the update. This is a shortcut to
1328 using :class:`.ColumnDefault` as a positional argument with
1329 ``for_update=True``.
1330  
1331 .. seealso::
1332  
1333 :ref:`metadata_defaults` - complete discussion of onupdate
1334  
1335 :param primary_key: If ``True``, marks this column as a primary key
1336 column. Multiple columns can have this flag set to specify
1337 composite primary keys. As an alternative, the primary key of a
1338 :class:`_schema.Table` can be specified via an explicit
1339 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` object.
1340  
1341 :param server_default: A :class:`.FetchedValue` instance, str, Unicode
1342 or :func:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text` construct representing
1343 the DDL DEFAULT value for the column.
1344  
1345 String types will be emitted as-is, surrounded by single quotes::
1346  
1347 Column('x', Text, server_default="val")
1348  
1349 x TEXT DEFAULT 'val'
1350  
1351 A :func:`~sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text` expression will be
1352 rendered as-is, without quotes::
1353  
1354 Column('y', DateTime, server_default=text('NOW()'))
1355  
1356 y DATETIME DEFAULT NOW()
1357  
1358 Strings and text() will be converted into a
1359 :class:`.DefaultClause` object upon initialization.
1360  
1361 Use :class:`.FetchedValue` to indicate that an already-existing
1362 column will generate a default value on the database side which
1363 will be available to SQLAlchemy for post-fetch after inserts. This
1364 construct does not specify any DDL and the implementation is left
1365 to the database, such as via a trigger.
1366  
1367 .. seealso::
1368  
1369 :ref:`server_defaults` - complete discussion of server side
1370 defaults
1371  
1372 :param server_onupdate: A :class:`.FetchedValue` instance
1373 representing a database-side default generation function,
1374 such as a trigger. This
1375 indicates to SQLAlchemy that a newly generated value will be
1376 available after updates. This construct does not actually
1377 implement any kind of generation function within the database,
1378 which instead must be specified separately.
1379  
1380  
1381 .. warning:: This directive **does not** currently produce MySQL's
1382 "ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()" clause. See
1383 :ref:`mysql_timestamp_onupdate` for background on how to
1384 produce this clause.
1385  
1386 .. seealso::
1387  
1388 :ref:`triggered_columns`
1389  
1390 :param quote: Force quoting of this column's name on or off,
1391 corresponding to ``True`` or ``False``. When left at its default
1392 of ``None``, the column identifier will be quoted according to
1393 whether the name is case sensitive (identifiers with at least one
1394 upper case character are treated as case sensitive), or if it's a
1395 reserved word. This flag is only needed to force quoting of a
1396 reserved word which is not known by the SQLAlchemy dialect.
1397  
1398 :param unique: When ``True``, and the :paramref:`_schema.Column.index`
1399 parameter is left at its default value of ``False``,
1400 indicates that a :class:`_schema.UniqueConstraint`
1401 construct will be automatically generated for this
1402 :class:`_schema.Column`,
1403 which will result in a "UNIQUE CONSTRAINT" clause referring
1404 to this column being included
1405 in the ``CREATE TABLE`` statement emitted, when the DDL create
1406 operation for the :class:`_schema.Table` object is invoked.
1407  
1408 When this flag is ``True`` while the
1409 :paramref:`_schema.Column.index` parameter is simultaneously
1410 set to ``True``, the effect instead is that a
1411 :class:`_schema.Index` construct which includes the
1412 :paramref:`_schema.Index.unique` parameter set to ``True``
1413 is generated. See the documentation for
1414 :paramref:`_schema.Column.index` for additional detail.
1415  
1416 Using this flag is equivalent to making use of the
1417 :class:`_schema.UniqueConstraint` construct explicitly at the
1418 level of the :class:`_schema.Table` construct itself::
1419  
1420 Table(
1421 "some_table",
1422 metadata,
1423 Column("x", Integer),
1424 UniqueConstraint("x")
1425 )
1426  
1427 The :paramref:`_schema.UniqueConstraint.name` parameter
1428 of the unique constraint object is left at its default value
1429 of ``None``; in the absence of a :ref:`naming convention <constraint_naming_conventions>`
1430 for the enclosing :class:`_schema.MetaData`, the UNIQUE CONSTRAINT
1431 construct will be emitted as unnamed, which typically invokes
1432 a database-specific naming convention to take place.
1433  
1434 As this flag is intended only as a convenience for the common case
1435 of adding a single-column, default configured unique constraint to a table
1436 definition, explicit use of the :class:`_schema.UniqueConstraint` construct
1437 should be preferred for most use cases, including composite constraints
1438 that encompass more than one column, backend-specific index configuration options, and
1439 constraints that use a specific name.
1440  
1441 .. note:: the :attr:`_schema.Column.unique` attribute on
1442 :class:`_schema.Column`
1443 **does not indicate** if this column has a unique constraint or
1444 not, only if this flag was explicitly set here. To view
1445 indexes and unique constraints that may involve this column,
1446 view the
1447 :attr:`_schema.Table.indexes` and/or
1448 :attr:`_schema.Table.constraints` collections or use
1449 :meth:`_reflection.Inspector.get_indexes` and/or
1450 :meth:`_reflection.Inspector.get_unique_constraints`
1451  
1452 .. seealso::
1453  
1454 :ref:`schema_unique_constraint`

1456 :ref:`constraint_naming_conventions`

1845 class ForeignKey(DialectKWArgs, SchemaItem):
1846 """Defines a dependency between two columns.
1847  
1848 ``ForeignKey`` is specified as an argument to a :class:`_schema.Column`
1849 object,
1850 e.g.::
1851  
1852 t = Table("remote_table", metadata,
1853 Column("remote_id", ForeignKey("main_table.id"))
1854 )
1855  
1856 Note that ``ForeignKey`` is only a marker object that defines
1857 a dependency between two columns. The actual constraint
1858 is in all cases represented by the :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint`
1859 object. This object will be generated automatically when
1860 a ``ForeignKey`` is associated with a :class:`_schema.Column` which
1861 in turn is associated with a :class:`_schema.Table`. Conversely,
1862 when :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint` is applied to a
1863 :class:`_schema.Table`,
1864 ``ForeignKey`` markers are automatically generated to be
1865 present on each associated :class:`_schema.Column`, which are also
1866 associated with the constraint object.
1867  
1868 Note that you cannot define a "composite" foreign key constraint,
1869 that is a constraint between a grouping of multiple parent/child
1870 columns, using ``ForeignKey`` objects. To define this grouping,
1871 the :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint` object must be used, and applied
1872 to the :class:`_schema.Table`. The associated ``ForeignKey`` objects
1873 are created automatically.
1874  
1875 The ``ForeignKey`` objects associated with an individual
1876 :class:`_schema.Column`
1877 object are available in the `foreign_keys` collection
1878 of that column.
1879  
1880 Further examples of foreign key configuration are in
1881 :ref:`metadata_foreignkeys`.
1882

3619 class PrimaryKeyConstraint(ColumnCollectionConstraint):
3620 """A table-level PRIMARY KEY constraint.
3621  
3622 The :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` object is present automatically
3623 on any :class:`_schema.Table` object; it is assigned a set of
3624 :class:`_schema.Column` objects corresponding to those marked with
3625 the :paramref:`_schema.Column.primary_key` flag::
3626  
3627 >>> my_table = Table('mytable', metadata,
3628 ... Column('id', Integer, primary_key=True),
3629 ... Column('version_id', Integer, primary_key=True),
3630 ... Column('data', String(50))
3631 ... )
3632 >>> my_table.primary_key
3633 PrimaryKeyConstraint(
3634 Column('id', Integer(), table=<mytable>,
3635 primary_key=True, nullable=False),
3636 Column('version_id', Integer(), table=<mytable>,
3637 primary_key=True, nullable=False)
3638 )
3639  
3640 The primary key of a :class:`_schema.Table` can also be specified by using
3641 a :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` object explicitly; in this mode of usage,
3642 the "name" of the constraint can also be specified, as well as other
3643 options which may be recognized by dialects::
3644  
3645 my_table = Table('mytable', metadata,
3646 Column('id', Integer),
3647 Column('version_id', Integer),
3648 Column('data', String(50)),
3649 PrimaryKeyConstraint('id', 'version_id',
3650 name='mytable_pk')
3651 )
3652  
3653 The two styles of column-specification should generally not be mixed.
3654 An warning is emitted if the columns present in the
3655 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint`
3656 don't match the columns that were marked as ``primary_key=True``, if both
3657 are present; in this case, the columns are taken strictly from the
3658 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` declaration, and those columns otherwise
3659 marked as ``primary_key=True`` are ignored. This behavior is intended to
3660 be backwards compatible with previous behavior.
3661  
3662 .. versionchanged:: 0.9.2 Using a mixture of columns within a
3663 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` in addition to columns marked as
3664 ``primary_key=True`` now emits a warning if the lists don't match.
3665 The ultimate behavior of ignoring those columns marked with the flag
3666 only is currently maintained for backwards compatibility; this warning
3667 may raise an exception in a future release.
3668  
3669 For the use case where specific options are to be specified on the
3670 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint`, but the usual style of using
3671 ``primary_key=True`` flags is still desirable, an empty
3672 :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` may be specified, which will take on the
3673 primary key column collection from the :class:`_schema.Table` based on the
3674 flags::
3675  
3676 my_table = Table('mytable', metadata,
3677 Column('id', Integer, primary_key=True),
3678 Column('version_id', Integer, primary_key=True),
3679 Column('data', String(50)),
3680 PrimaryKeyConstraint(name='mytable_pk',
3681 mssql_clustered=True)
3682 )
3683  
3684 .. versionadded:: 0.9.2 an empty :class:`.PrimaryKeyConstraint` may now
3685 be specified for the purposes of establishing keyword arguments with
3686 the constraint, independently of the specification of "primary key"
3687 columns within the :class:`_schema.Table` itself; columns marked as
3688 ``primary_key=True`` will be gathered into the empty constraint's
3689 column collection.
3690  
3691 """
3692

3848 class Index(DialectKWArgs, ColumnCollectionMixin, SchemaItem):
3849 """A table-level INDEX.
3850  
3851 Defines a composite (one or more column) INDEX.
3852  
3853 E.g.::
3854  
3855 sometable = Table("sometable", metadata,
3856 Column("name", String(50)),
3857 Column("address", String(100))
3858 )

3862 For a no-frills, single column index, adding
3863 :class:`_schema.Column` also supports ``index=True``::
3864

3866 Column("name", String(50), index=True)
3867 )

3870

3874 :data:`.func` construct in conjunction with table-bound
3875 :class:`_schema.Column` objects::
3876

3880 :class:`_schema.Table`,

3882 :meth:`_schema.Table.append_constraint`. When this approach is used,

3885

3887 Column("name", String(50)),
3888 Column("address", String(100)),

3893 :func:`_expression.text` construct may be used::
3894  
3895 from sqlalchemy import text

3898 Column("name", String(50)),
3899 Column("address", String(100)),

3901 )

4118 when this option is set.
4119  
4120 :param schema:
4121 The default schema to use for the :class:`_schema.Table`,
4122 :class:`.Sequence`, and potentially other objects associated with
4123 this :class:`_schema.MetaData`. Defaults to ``None``.
4124  
4125 When this value is set, any :class:`_schema.Table` or
4126 :class:`.Sequence`
4127 which specifies ``None`` for the schema parameter will instead
4128 have this schema name defined. To build a :class:`_schema.Table`
4129 or :class:`.Sequence` that still has ``None`` for the schema
4130 even when this parameter is present, use the :attr:`.BLANK_SCHEMA`
4131 symbol.
4132  
4133 .. note::
4134  
4135 As referred above, the :paramref:`_schema.MetaData.schema`
4136 parameter
4137 only refers to the **default value** that will be applied to
4138 the :paramref:`_schema.Table.schema` parameter of an incoming
4139 :class:`_schema.Table` object. It does not refer to how the
4140 :class:`_schema.Table` is catalogued within the
4141 :class:`_schema.MetaData`,
4142 which remains consistent vs. a :class:`_schema.MetaData`
4143 collection
4144 that does not define this parameter. The
4145 :class:`_schema.Table`
4146 within the :class:`_schema.MetaData`
4147 will still be keyed based on its
4148 schema-qualified name, e.g.
4149 ``my_metadata.tables["some_schema.my_table"]``.
4150  
4151 The current behavior of the :class:`_schema.ForeignKey`
4152 object is to
4153 circumvent this restriction, where it can locate a table given
4154 the table name alone, where the schema will be assumed to be
4155 present from this value as specified on the owning
4156 :class:`_schema.MetaData` collection. However,
4157 this implies that a
4158 table qualified with BLANK_SCHEMA cannot currently be referred
4159 to by string name from :class:`_schema.ForeignKey`.
4160 Other parts of
4161 SQLAlchemy such as Declarative may not have similar behaviors
4162 built in, however may do so in a future release, along with a
4163 consistent method of referring to a table in BLANK_SCHEMA.
4164  
4165  
4166 .. seealso::
4167  
4168 :paramref:`_schema.Table.schema`
4169  
4170 :paramref:`.Sequence.schema`
4171  
4172 :param quote_schema:
4173 Sets the ``quote_schema`` flag for those :class:`_schema.Table`,
4174 :class:`.Sequence`, and other objects which make usage of the
4175 local ``schema`` name.
4176  
4177 :param info: Optional data dictionary which will be populated into the
4178 :attr:`.SchemaItem.info` attribute of this object.
4179  
4180 .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
4181  
4182 :param naming_convention: a dictionary referring to values which
4183 will establish default naming conventions for :class:`.Constraint`
4184 and :class:`.Index` objects, for those objects which are not given
4185 a name explicitly.
4186  
4187 The keys of this dictionary may be:
4188  
4189 * a constraint or Index class, e.g. the :class:`.UniqueConstraint`,
4190 :class:`_schema.ForeignKeyConstraint` class, the :class:`.Index`
4191 class
4192  
4193 * a string mnemonic for one of the known constraint classes;
4194 ``"fk"``, ``"pk"``, ``"ix"``, ``"ck"``, ``"uq"`` for foreign key,
4195 primary key, index, check, and unique constraint, respectively.
4196  
4197 * the string name of a user-defined "token" that can be used
4198 to define new naming tokens.
4199  
4200 The values associated with each "constraint class" or "constraint
4201 mnemonic" key are string naming templates, such as
4202 ``"uq_%(table_name)s_%(column_0_name)s"``,
4203 which describe how the name should be composed. The values
4204 associated with user-defined "token" keys should be callables of the
4205 form ``fn(constraint, table)``, which accepts the constraint/index
4206 object and :class:`_schema.Table` as arguments, returning a string
4207 result.
4208  
4209 The built-in names are as follows, some of which may only be
4210 available for certain types of constraint:
4211  
4212 * ``%(table_name)s`` - the name of the :class:`_schema.Table`
4213 object
4214 associated with the constraint.
4215  
4216 * ``%(referred_table_name)s`` - the name of the

4463 def reflect(
4464 self,

4474 r"""Load all available table definitions from the database.
4475  
4476 Automatically creates ``Table`` entries in this ``MetaData`` for any
4477 table available in the database but not yet present in the
4478 ``MetaData``. May be called multiple times to pick up tables recently
4479 added to the database, however no special action is taken if a table
4480 in this ``MetaData`` no longer exists in the database.
4481

4490

4492 If True, also reflect views.
4493

4496 specified as a sequence of names or a callable.
4497

4499 reflected. An error is raised if a table is requested but not
4500 available. Named tables already present in this ``MetaData`` are
4501 ignored.
4502  
4503 If a callable is provided, it will be used as a boolean predicate to
4504 filter the list of potential table names. The callable is called
4505 with a table name and this ``MetaData`` instance as positional
4506 arguments and should return a true value for any table to reflect.

4509 :paramref:`_schema.Table.extend_existing`.

4515 :paramref:`_schema.Table.autoload_replace`.

4520 objects linked
4521 to :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` objects located in each
4522 :class:`_schema.Table`.
4523 For :meth:`_schema.MetaData.reflect`,
4524 this has the effect of reflecting
4525 related tables that might otherwise not be in the list of tables
4526 being reflected, for example if the referenced table is in a
4527 different schema or is omitted via the
4528 :paramref:`.MetaData.reflect.only` parameter. When False,
4529 :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` objects are not followed to the
4530 :class:`_schema.Table`
4531 in which they link, however if the related table is also part of the
4532 list of tables that would be reflected in any case, the
4533 :class:`_schema.ForeignKey` object will still resolve to its related
4534 :class:`_schema.Table` after the :meth:`_schema.MetaData.reflect`
4535 operation is
4536 complete. Defaults to True.

4539

4541  
4542 :paramref:`_schema.Table.resolve_fks`

4551 :paramref:`.MetaData.reflect.**dialect_kwargs` to support

4556 if bind is None:

4560

4562 "autoload": True,
4563 "autoload_with": conn,
4564 "extend_existing": extend_existing,
4565 "autoload_replace": autoload_replace,
4566 "resolve_fks": resolve_fks,
4567 "_extend_on": set(),
4568 }

4571  
4572 if schema is None:
4573 schema = self.schema
4574  
4575 if schema is not None:
4576 reflect_opts["schema"] = schema
4577  
4578 available = util.OrderedSet(
4579 bind.engine.table_names(schema, connection=conn)
4580 )
4581 if views:
4582 available.update(bind.dialect.get_view_names(conn, schema))
4583

4586 ["%s.%s" % (schema, name) for name in available]

4588 else:
4589 available_w_schema = available

4597 if extend_existing or schname not in current
4598 ]

4601 name
4602 for name, schname in zip(available, available_w_schema)
4603 if (extend_existing or schname not in current)

4695 class ThreadLocalMetaData(MetaData):
4696 """A MetaData variant that presents a different ``bind`` in every thread.
4697  
4698 Makes the ``bind`` property of the MetaData a thread-local value, allowing
4699 this collection of tables to be bound to different ``Engine``
4700 implementations or connections in each thread.
4701  
4702 The ThreadLocalMetaData starts off bound to None in each thread. Binds
4703 must be made explicitly by assigning to the ``bind`` property or using
4704 ``connect()``. You can also re-bind dynamically multiple times per
4705 thread, just like a regular ``MetaData``.
4706  
4707 """
4708  
4709 __visit_name__ = "metadata"
4710  
4711 def __init__(self):
4712 """Construct a ThreadLocalMetaData."""
4713  
4714 self.context = util.threading.local()
4715 self.__engines = {}
4716 super(ThreadLocalMetaData, self).__init__()
4717  
4718 def bind(self):
4719 """The bound Engine or Connection for this thread.
4720  
4721 This property may be assigned an Engine or Connection, or assigned a
4722 string or URL to automatically create a basic Engine for this bind
4723 with ``create_engine()``."""
4724  
4725 return getattr(self.context, "_engine", None)
4726  
4727 @util.dependencies("sqlalchemy.engine.url")
4728 def _bind_to(self, url, bind):
4729 """Bind to a Connectable in the caller's thread."""
4730  
4731 if isinstance(bind, util.string_types + (url.URL,)):
4732 try:
4733 self.context._engine = self.__engines[bind]
4734 except KeyError:
4735 e = sqlalchemy.create_engine(bind)
4736 self.__engines[bind] = e
4737 self.context._engine = e
4738 else:
4739 # TODO: this is squirrely. we shouldn't have to hold onto engines
4740 # in a case like this
4741 if bind not in self.__engines:
4742 self.__engines[bind] = bind
4743 self.context._engine = bind

4751 and self.context._engine is not None

4844 """Construct a GENERATED ALWAYS AS DDL construct to accompany a
4845 :class:`_schema.Column`.
